nformality.In this book, Chandan Deuskar explores how politicians in developing democracies provide urban land and services to the urban poor in exchange for their political support, demonstrates how this impacts urban growth, and suggests innovative and practical ways in which urban planners can try to be more effective in this challenging political context. He draws on literature from multiple disciplines (urban planning, political science, sociology, anthropology, and others), statistical analysis of global data on urbanization, and an in-depth case study of urban Ghana.Urban planners and international development experts working in the Global South, as well as researchers, educators, and students of global urbanization will find Urban Planning in a World of Informal Politics informative and thought-provoking.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aCity planningxPolitical aspectszDeveloping countries. 0aCity planningxPolitical aspectszGhana. 0aPatron and clientzDeveloping countries. 0aPatron and clientzGhana. 0aSquatter settlementszGhana. 0aUrbanizationxPolitical aspectszDeveloping countries. 4aInterdisciplinary-African Studies. 4aInterdisciplinary-Urban Studies. 4aPolitical Science/Public Policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh  aGhana.  aaffordable housing.  aclientelism.  aglobal South.  aglobalization.  agovernance.  ahow cities grow.  ainformal politics.  ainformal settlements.  ainfrastructure.  alandowner.  alocal.  aneoliberalism.  apatronage.  apolitical support.  apoor poverty.  apublic services.  aslums.  aurban expansion.  aurban planning.  avotes.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076767440uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/97